# 🧠 Concept 1: How to Mentally Execute a Program

## ✅ The Biggest Mistake Students Make

Many students look at code and guess.

Interviewers don't want guesses.

They want:

👉 Step-by-step execution.

---

## 💡 Real-World Analogy

Imagine you're following a Google Maps route 🗺️

You don't magically jump to the destination.

You move one step at a time.

Programs work the same way.

---

# 🔥 Golden Rule

When predicting output:

Always track:

1. Variable values
2. Loop conditions
3. Function calls
4. Memory changes

---

## Example 1

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main()
{
    int a = 5;

    a = a + 2;

    printf("%d", a);

    return 0;
}
```

---

### Step-by-Step

Initially:

```text
a = 5
```

Then:

```c
a = a + 2;
```

becomes:

```text
a = 7
```

Output:

```text
7
```

---

## 🧠 Memory Trick

Never jump directly to output.

Follow every line.

---

# 🔥 Example 2 (Interview Favorite)

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main()
{
    int x = 10;

    printf("%d %d", x, x++);

    return 0;
}
```

---

## ⚠️ Important

Many students try to predict this.

But this is actually:

# 🚨 Undefined Behavior

Why?

Because:

```c
x
```

and

```c
x++
```

modify/access the same variable in one statement without a guaranteed evaluation order.

---

## Interview Answer

Instead of guessing output:

Say:

> "This code has undefined behavior in C."

🔥 Interviewers love this answer.

